John Edward: The Language Skills That the World's Citizens Need
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, and the added weight to this is given by individual and joint successes in sport, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the aforementioned school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his mother tongue, it goes to his heart."
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot only use the English language if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of this year's final exams show that the highest scores in languages have been achieved by students of independent schools.
A total of 68% of pupils who learned foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils received an excellent score for the Mandarin language, while 72% of pupils who learn German, 69% of pupils who learn French and 63% of pupils who learn Spanish were also the most likely.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 % of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of language skills workforce.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs demand language skills, these skills are key in a globalised world.
Regardless of your career choice, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such long-term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, which gives him an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov, which involved more than 4,000 adults in 2013, 75% of respondents in the UK do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, namely 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing economies, they will have more opportunities to find a good job.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their program, while others will opt for languages that are considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, in independent schools there will always be a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools provide children with an environment in which they will learn to prepare and equip themselves with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds for us.
One cannot ignore the fact that in today's global business age, language skills are very important for the future of each country, so that must also be reflected in education.
Thus, the knowledge of modern languages should indeed be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer a choice of languages, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Council of Scottish Independent Schools.
