The new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to sleep well in an attempt to combat an increasingly widespread culture of learning with caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed a course he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea of the course after giving a speech on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, “Why did I find out this only now, in my last year of college?”
"She said no one told her how important the dream was, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains how good sleep habits help in academic and sporting success and generally improve health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's executive director of health care, said the university had decided to introduce the course after students had a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a student bedroom where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how sleep deprivation affects success, and how important a sleep routine is.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
After that, a campus map with interactive icons is shown that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know how cigarettes affect health,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in full-time learning before the exam continues to exist, says the professor and adds that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be good and quality sleep. Sleep also helps in the fight against obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it into a state of hunger and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemistry and biology from California, helped Professor Chaisler devise the course after attending his lectures in his first year at Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As the next step, it plans to ask all graduates to complete a similar course of study before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause problems with sleep.
